The SING Nigeria Observer team which was led by Comrade Okpanachi Jacob started its observation activity at 8:00AM in Oredo Local Government Area, Edo State. The indication from most of the polling units visited revealed that the voting process was characterised by logistical challenges as materials arrived late, despite the impressive turnout and energetic participation of voters. At ward 2 Georgina Idah, the team observed that there was poor adherence to COVID-19 protocols, as a large crowd of voters queued without observing physical distancing rules. At 8:47AM, the team arrived at Ebenezer polling units 6 & 7, ward 2 where it was observed that there were no INEC officials or materials in sight, only a large number of voters queued up, waiting to exercise their franchise. The impact of the delay was evident in the conclusion of the voting process as it translated to a late collation of results in some polling units. While the process can be said to be reasonably fair, reports from SING volunteers and observers in other local governments recorded pockets of voter intimidation, and squabble among agents. This was preceded by reports of compromise of some security agents as thugs were allowed to barge on the process without interference. It can also be noted that there were visible vote-buying activities in various polling units. Despite delays of materials and pockets of vote-buying, election at Oredo local government can be said to be devoid of rigging in most of the polling units visited.
In line with SING’s pet project #EndMoneyPolitics, they urge Nigerians to seek for better alternatives in elections rather than sell their vote.